Assignment 5 - k-Means Algorithm

  • Load needed libraries: tidyverse, stats, ggfortify and factoextra

    library(tidyverse)

library(factoextra)
    ## Welcome! Want to learn more? See two factoextra-related books at https://goo.gl/ve3WBa

  1. Load the dataset mammal_Sleep.csv into a data frame.

    df_sleep <- read.csv("mammal_Sleep.csv")

  2. Create a new data frame sleep_data with sleep_total and sleep_rem.

    sleep_data <- df_sleep[,7:8]

  • Check for incomplete cases

    sleep_data %>% 
  filter(!complete.cases(.)) %>% 
  view

  • There are 22 cases with NA in sleep_rem. These will be replaced with the mean value for sleep_rem.

  • Calculate the mean and median value for sleep_rem

    mean_sleep_rem <- mean(sleep_data$sleep_rem, na.rm = TRUE)
median_sleep_rem <- median(sleep_data$sleep_rem, na.rm = TRUE)
mean_sleep_rem
    ## [1] 1.87541
    median_sleep_rem
    ## [1] 1.5

  • These values are quite close. Graph a histogram of the sleep_rem variable to examine its distribution:

    df_sleep %>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=sleep_rem)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  labs(title="REM sleep histogram",
       x = "REM sleep time",
       y = "Count of mammals")
    ## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
    ## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_bin()`).

  • This histogram of sleep_rem shows it is somewhat right skewed, but there shouldnt be much difference whether mean or median is used to replace NA values.

  • Replace sleep_rem with NA by mean sleep_rem using replace_na

    sleep_data <- sleep_data %>% 
  replace_na(list(sleep_rem = mean_sleep_rem))

  • Check again for incomplete cases

    sleep_data %>% 
  filter(!complete.cases(.)) %>% 
  view

  • No Incomplete cases

  • Scale the dataset

    sleep_data_scale <- scale(sleep_data)

  • Use three different graphs to evaluate how many clusters should be used

  • First use wss plot. The elbow shows the suggested number of clusters.

    fviz_nbclust(sleep_data_scale, kmeans, method="wss") +
  labs(subtitle = "Elbow method")

  • Next the silhouette method

    fviz_nbclust(sleep_data_scale, kmeans, method="silhouette") +
  labs(subtitle = "Silhouette method")

  • Finally the gap stat method

    fviz_nbclust(sleep_data_scale, kmeans, method="gap_stat") +
  labs(subtitle = "Gap stat method")

  1. Fit a k-means clustering model with 4 clusters to the data subset sleep_data scale.
sleep_model_km <- kmeans(sleep_data_scale, centers=4, nstart =10)

  • Use autoplot to graph clusters, first with a boundary around the clusters.

    autoplot(sleep_model_km, sleep_data_scale, frame = TRUE)

  • Plot with autoplot again with no boundary around the clusters.

    autoplot(sleep_model_km, sleep_data_scale)

  • The axes on these plots are labeled PC1 and PC2, meaning they use principal components to display the clusters.

  • Use fviz_cluster to display the cluster against the scaled values of sleep_total and sleep_rem.

    km.clusters <- sleep_model_km$cluster
fviz_cluster(list(data=sleep_data_scale, 
                  cluster = km.clusters))

  1. Find the centroids of the clusters in the model on the chart.

  • The centroids are visible in the above chart as the labeled larger colored symbols in the center of the clusters: an orange diamond for cluster 1, a green triangle for cluster 2, a blue square for cluster 3 and a purple cross for cluster 4.

  • The data points in the above graph are labeled with the IDs of the observations. If we want to see how the vore feature corresponds to the clusters, we can label the data points with the vore feature as well as their IDs.

    rownames(sleep_data_scale) <- paste(df_sleep$vore,
                              1:dim(df_sleep)[1],
                              sep="_")
fviz_cluster(list(data=sleep_data_scale, 
                  cluster = km.clusters))

  • We can also use a table to see how the vore variable is divided into clusters:

    table(km.clusters, df_sleep$vore)
    ##            
## km.clusters carni herbi insecti omni
##           1     5    12       1    4
##           2     7     7       2   15
##           3     1     0       2    1
##           4     6    13       0    0

  • This shows the clusters partially separate mammals by vore, but there is are also multiple vore features in each cluster, so perhaps other variables could also be considered to examine their relationship to these clusters.
